The Enhanced Russell Graph measure, deï¬ned as the optimal value of the above model, satisï¬es several interesting properties from a mathematical and economic point of view. However,
it presents a limitation, a weakness shared with other traditional measures in DEA. Speciï¬cally, the original Enhanced Russell Graph measure minimizes technical eï¬ƒciency in equation
1. In order to maximize instead of minimize technical eï¬ƒciency, it seems suï¬ƒcient to change
â€œminâ€ for â€œmaxâ€ in equation 1. However, this is not true. In this case, we could show that the
solutions generated by the model would not be technically eï¬ƒcient, but ineï¬ƒcient (see [4]) and,
therefore, could not serve as valid benchmark for the assessed DMU.
This problem was behind the introduction of diï¬€erent approaches to maximizing technical eï¬ƒciency suitably in DEA. Some of these approaches propose using Mixed Integer Linear
Programs to overcome the problem [4]. In the case of DMU k, the model to be solved would
