One weakness of the approach in equation 2 is that it uses a â€œbig M â€ to model the key
constraints (c.7) and (c.8). Speciï¬cally, it allows us to link djk to Î±jk by means of the binary
variable bjk . The value of M can be calculated if and only if all the facets that deï¬ne the
technology are previously determined. Unfortunately, the identiï¬cation of all these facets is a
combinatorial NP-hard problem. Something similar happens with the other approaches devoted
to maximizing technical eï¬ƒciency. All of them are related in some sense to a big M or the
direct calculation of all the eï¬ƒcient facets (see Jahanshahloo et al. [11, 12, 13]).
In this paper, we apply a Genetic Algorithm to solve equation 2. In order to check the
goodness of our approach, the results are compared with those obtained from the determination
of all the facets of the frontier in DEA using a set of simulated numerical examples.
